  GNU Pth - The GNU Portable Threads

  INSTALL
  =======

  Requirements
  ------------

  o  CMake >= 3.19
  o  A C compiler (GCC or Clang)
  o  A Bourne shell (`sh`), used to run the bundled `shtool` to generate
     `pth_p.h` at configure time
  o  x86_64 or arm64/aarch64 on Linux, FreeBSD, or macOS

  Quick Start
  -----------

  To configure, build, test and install the Pth library:

    $ cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX=/path/to/pth [OPTIONS]
    $ cmake --build build
    $ ctest --test-dir build --output-on-failure
    $ cmake --install build

  This installs into /path/to/pth/{bin,lib,include,man}/. If
  -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX is omitted, the default is /usr/local.

  Pth Options
  -----------

  Pass these as -D<OPTION>=<VALUE> to the first `cmake` invocation above.

  PTH_BUILD_TESTS=ON|OFF (default=ON)
      Build the test_xxx programs and register them with ctest.

  PTH_BUILD_PTHREAD=ON|OFF (default=OFF)
      Build and install the POSIX Threads ("pthread") emulation library
      (libpthread built on top of Pth). Forces PTH_SYSCALL_SOFT=ON.

  PTH_MP=ON|OFF (default=ON)
      Enable multi-scheduler (M:N, multi-CPU) support: N cooperative
      schedulers on N OS threads. See MULTISCHED-DESIGN.md.

  PTH_DEBUG=ON|OFF (default=OFF)
      Build with Pth's internal debugging output. Only interesting for
      developers.

  PTH_SYSCALL_SOFT=ON|OFF (default=OFF)
      Enable the soft system call mapping (pth_read() etc. as macros over
      the real calls) in pth.h and pthread.h.

  PTH_SYSCALL_HARD=ON|OFF (default=OFF)
      Enable the hard system call mapping in pth_syscall.c, i.e. libpth
      exports wrapper symbols for read(2), write(2), etc.

  PTH_SCHED_POLL=ON|OFF (default=ON)
      Use poll(2) instead of select(2) in the scheduler core (removes the
      FD_SETSIZE ceiling).

  PTH_SCHED_EPOLL=ON|OFF (default: ON on Linux, OFF elsewhere)
      Use epoll(7) persistent readiness registration in the scheduler
      core. Linux only; implies PTH_SCHED_POLL. Mutually exclusive with
      PTH_SCHED_KQUEUE.

  PTH_SCHED_KQUEUE=ON|OFF (default: ON on *BSD/macOS, OFF elsewhere)
      Use kqueue(2) persistent readiness registration in the scheduler
      core. *BSD/macOS only; implies PTH_SCHED_POLL.

  BUILD_SHARED_LIBS=ON|OFF (default=OFF)
      Build libpth (and libpthread, if enabled) as a shared library
      instead of static.

  PTH_MCTX_MTH=mcsc|bctx (default: autodetect; mcsc on Linux/FreeBSD,
  bctx on macOS)                                       [EXPERTS ONLY]
      Force the machine-context (thread stack switching) method:
      mcsc .... makecontext(2)/swapcontext(2) (SVR4/SUSv2 ucontext)
      bctx .... Boost.Context fcontext (vendored assembly); required on
                macOS/Apple Silicon, selectable on any target.

  PTH_SYSCALL_LIBS=PATH[:PATH...]                      [EXPERTS ONLY]
      Colon-separated libc paths to search when resolving the real
      system calls for PTH_SYSCALL_HARD.

  Compiler Flags
  --------------

  Some systems require unusual options for compilation or linking. Pass
  them to CMake via the standard variables, e.g.:

    $ cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=clang -DCMAKE_C_FLAGS=-O2

  Installation Names
  -------------------

  By default, `cmake --install` places files under `/usr/local/{bin,lib,
  include,man}`. Set a different prefix with -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX=PATH
  on the initial `cmake -S . -B build` invocation, or override it at
  install time with `cmake --install build --prefix PATH`.

  Using the Installed Library
  ----------------------------

  A pkg-config file is installed alongside the library:

    $ cc myapp.c $(pkg-config --cflags --libs pth) -o myapp

  Or link directly: `-lpth`, plus `-pthread` if built with PTH_MP=ON.
  Projects that consume Pth via CMake's `find_package`/`add_subdirectory`
  can link against the `pth` target directly.
